Books

Sex and the City

By EDMUND WHITEFEB. 21, 1999



Continue reading the main story
Share This Page

Continue reading the main story









ALLAN STEINBy Matthew Stadler.256 pp. New York:Grove Press. $22.WRITERS today explore the boundary between fact and fiction in many ways, some acknowledged and shared with the reader from the beginning, others sprung on the reader unexpectedly. There's nothing hidden or underhanded about Matthew Stadler's mix of fact and fiction in ''Allan Stein.'' A first-person narrator named Matthew goes to Paris pursuing information about Allan Stein, Gertrude Stein's unexceptional nephew, who died long before. In particular, Matthew hopes to find Picasso's missing 1906 drawings of the boy (which probably never existed). The novel ends with a bibliography (real, not fictitious) that lists 16 titles quoted in the text, including seven early-20th-century travel books, letters of members of the Stein family, memoirs of people who knew the Steins and two of Gertrude Stein's published works. So much for the fact side of the equation, although even in this domain the research is desultory and nonprofessional, and the narrator finds in it what he wants to.On the fiction side there is the story of an assumed identity as ''Matthew'' takes on the name and occupation of a friend, a museum curator named Herbert Widener; and there is a love story between this false Herbert and a 15-year-old Parisian named Stephane, a pursuit that roughly parallels Matthew's detective work into the life of Allan Stein. This parallel is loosely encompassed by the haunting epigraph from Gertrude Stein: ''What is the use of being a boy if you grow up to become a man, what is the use?''To complicate the story further, the narrator is constantly recalling his own past as a teen-ager. He remembers a day by the sea when he was already erotically fascinated by a man his mother had just encountered on the beach. The adult narrator half-lusts after his own 14-year-old self; we might call this strategy the pedophilia of autobiography. He also recalls his first trip to Paris as an adolescent. Although he and his mother agreed to go their separate ways by day, young Matthew actually followed his mother everywhere. Now, in the present of the novel, 15 years later, Matthew tails Stephane as the boy cycles rapidly through Paris. In both cases this secret shadowing takes on a sexual excitement for him. As does his pursuit of Allan Stein through time.Although this book is organized around two obsessions (for Stephane and Allan), it manages, despite its brevity, to take in great swaths of experience -- among other topics, the international art scene, Stephane's bohemian French-Dutch family, the natural splendor of the American Pacific Northwest. But the obsessions form the thread that pulls us through the labyrinth of the city, for ''Allan Stein'' belongs to a very old literary tradition. The genre includes August Strindberg's ''Inferno,'' Knut Hamsun's ''Hunger,'' Andre Breton's ''Nadja'' and Thomas McGuane's ''Ninety-two in the Shade''; in each of them someone obsessed with love (or, in Strindberg's case, his own paranoid delusions) discovers a city or town in an aleatory way.

Advertisement

Continue reading the main story

What makes ''Allan Stein'' unusual is the lyric suppleness and restraint of the writing, a kind of mandarin American casualness that is peculiar to such West Coast writers as Dennis Cooper, Dodie Bellamy, Kevin Killian and Robert Gluck, a school of refined but deceptively offhand stylists. Matthew Stadler is its newest star. In ''Allan Stein'' we encounter the trademark passages of stark beauty alternating with throwaway references to pop culture. When Matthew sees Stephane playing basketball, he realizes the kid has picked up the mannerisms of African-American athletes: ''An inner-city slouch (transmitted via music television) like some kind of dybbuk bled from gray tin air into this thin French boy's body and, split-second channel-change style, I found myself standing beside a jaded gangbanger (sweet-faced, just guessing really), scopin' for his homies.''
Newsletter Sign Up
Continue reading the main story

  


