This novel, like Stadler's earlier ones (''Landscape: Memory,'' ''The Sex Offender'' and ''The Dissolution of Nicholas Dee''), pursues its subtle, post-modernist course through the aftermath of gay fiction. We might call what Stadler -- along with Michael Cunningham and Dale Peck -- writes post-gay fiction, since these writers no longer seal off gay characters in a ghetto where the main goal is self-definition or public acceptance. These novelists, though quick to acknowledge their own homosexuality, set their characters spinning through the great world (sometimes the gay character is a minor one, as in ''The Hours,'' by Michael Cunningham).In ''Allan Stein'' the narrator, perhaps because he loves adolescents, faintly despises adult homosexuals (and heterosexuals): ''I don't know why conservative, drunk ex-husbands in tract houses watching TV news exposes are so easily convinced the gay demimonde is sex-saturated and glamorous. In fact it is just as tacky and crass as the worst G.I. Shenanigans bar in the most sexless highway strip mall of the most forlorn suburban development . . . and if the terrific gains of gay liberation continue apace we'll soon be joining these straight potbellied swingles on the margins of those 12-lane highways that seem to go on forever and ever into a false dusk of sodium-vapor lights.'' Love among adults and the inferno of the American mall are invoked only to contrast them with the paradise of Paris and Stephane on his bicycle: ''I watched his strong legs, his slim back and shoulders, and saw everything I could ever love contained within the encyclopedic completeness of this solemn angel leading me into the evening traffic.'' Continue reading the main story







Advertisement

Continue reading the main story





That this novel has an aspect of ''Lolita'' may trouble some readers, though it is a lot less sex-obsessed than ''Lolita.'' I was slightly put off by the gambit of the narrator posing as someone else. It would have been so easy to eliminate this overly familiar complication. But Stadler has always gone in for post-modernist high jinks (in ''The Dissolution of Nicholas Dee,'' the main character is writing a history of insurance that bizarrely evolves into the chronicle of the creation of an opera house in the 17th-century Netherlands). ''Allan Stein'' may still bear the faint marks of such fussy experimentalism, but it is powered by passion. With it Stadler demonstrates that he is among the handful of first-rate young American novelists, one with a wide reach and a quirky, elegant pen. The writing and the composition of this evocation of the Paris cityscape and its seductive denizens are remarkable. Continue reading the main story






